<rating>5</rating>< review>
I'm writing this review to share my sincere gratitude and appreciation for the Ballpark Self Storage team. Adam, Sam and their entire staff were so terrific to interact with as I was grinding through my recent Downtown move. For any of you that have relocated from one Downtown condo rise to another, I'm sure you can relate to the challenging HOA bureaucracy that's involved with scheduling, coordinating and completing the transition of your items. I had to rent their U-Haul van three separate times over the course of eight days to complete my move and each time I arrived to pick it up I found them to be the singularly positive part of my day. They were extremely accommodating with the pick-up and drop off each time and actually waived some normally charged add-ons like the dolly rental or gas usage each time I came in. On top of that, the second time I came in I needed some of those packing peanuts and instead of charging me whatever each for the smaller bags they sell the awesome lady helping me said, "I just put two big garbage bags full of them in our dumpster if you'd like to have them." They were like brand new and saved me about $40! I've never even heard of someone doing anything like that! Now don't get me wrong, these people are running a business and no one should expect a ton of freebies from a place that needs to turn a profit, but they certainly rewarded my customer loyalty and repeat business. I can honestly give my highest possible praise and recommendation for the Ballpark Self Storage team and wouldn't think of using another company for a future move or storage unit rental. I wish I could give them 10 Stars, they'd deserve them all! Thanks so very much for everything Ballpark Team, and I wish you all a wonderful Holiday Season!< /review>

<Review>I have been renting a storage unit at Ballpark Self Storage for almost 5 years. Besides its desirable locations, right at the heart of downtown San Diego, the treatment I have been receiving from Adam's team is superb customer service (friendly, respectful and helpful). I think they have clearly been implementing and understood the critical element of customer service of  the good ol'days notion “customer is king” in their marketing strategy, which adds value to their service in order so as to create loyal and satisfied customers, and they have been able to  retain their clients  for so long. However, as compared to their location and other competing facilities in the vicinity, their price for different size storage units are fairly decent. < review>
With so much negativity coursing through the world I very very rarely chime in with a negative review (besides Fate takes care of things much better than I ever could), but the callous disregard was too much to let slide. Copy Center clerk could barely be bothered to even point me toward a copy machine. <Text>Definitely the Greatest Vietnamese sandwich I have had thus far.

This is a small mom and pop shop selling some sundries and sandwiches.

With Vietnamese sandwich, the owner offered me a free complimentary Vietnamese tea and cookie.

The sandwich was very simple, yet refreshing. Served on a semi-baguette Vietnamese style, with some pork meats, and pickles sauce. The sweetness contrast nicely with the banh-mi style garnishes such as thinly sliced raw jalapeños.

For less than nine dollars with all the complimentary throw-ins, would definitely come back here again.< /Text><time>1609177051231< /time>< GmapID>

<Rate>5< /Rate>< text>
Sandwich House is a must try! They are my favorite banh mi sandwiches and really, one of my favorite restaurants in OC! Not only is their food delicious, but it is run by some of the kindest people. You are met with so much kindness and hospitality - the best customer service ever! They even give all of their customers complentary iced tea with each order.

My favorite meal is their #1 Sandwich House Special with an avocado smoothie! Highly recommend, but really everything that I've tried on the menu is delicious. I also love the #21 BBQ chicken on a croissant with an added fried egg added on top! Also their homemade buttered toast/biscuts are amazing! They make look simple, but you have to try a box. Once you start, you won't be able to stop - so good!

I've been going here for years and will continue to because food that is made with love always tastes better and Vu and Ann truly do love their customers!< /text>

<username>Julie Ghim</username><date>1599629960471<//date><rating>5</rating><Text>Ahn and Vu have always been my favorite place for bahn mi or croissant sandwiches. I’ve been a regular for several years now and they never fail me. I usually go for the #4 or the #19 (without onions). The beef stew is also excellent on a chilly day, available w/baguette or vermicelli noodles!

They remember my face/name, my order, what I’ve been up to lately, etc. Recently due to covid they haven’t been getting as much business from the bulk of their customers at Cypress College across the street. Small businesses are always the most vulnerable in times such as these.

Free sugared toast and jasmine iced tea with every order, and you can call ahead for pick-up to streamline the whole process. Please support this lovely sandwich shop- you won’t regret it! :)<//Text>< pics>

<Response>None< /Response>< review>
The Sandwich House across from Cypress College has, hands down, the best Vietnamese sandwiches and coffee.  What makes it truly special is the man behind the counter.  He is warm, kind, and loves his patrons.  Now during our isolation, since we place our order either over the phone or at the counter then wait outside, he adds an dose of extra kindness, with free cinnamon crisps or cookies.  For favorite customers it might be free iced tea as well.  The person who makes the sandwiches is generous with the ingredients, always served on the freshest of baguette or croissant.  Thank you, Sandwich House!<//review>

<Rating>1</Rating><Review>Let me start off by saying I really wanted to like this place and support local mom and pop business, unfortunately, their food had let me down too many times.

The good:
The friendly service from both the husband and wife were great and they are really friendly people that offer free iced tea and provide an excellent experience. Sad to say, that's pretty much it.

The bad:
I've seen other bad reviews about the lack of actual meat in their sandwiches but thought it might have been a one off or just a picky customer, but nope, its really true.  I really have this place a chance and have been here multiple times and every time I get at least one underwhelming sandwich and even a missing sandwich on a large order to go. Lastly, their pricing is higher than vietnamese sandwich shops in Westminister. Soooo ... high pricing and poor quality food is a no go for me. Im probably not coming back here again.

Last words:
There isn't enough free iced tea that can make up  for this.<//Review><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN3lmNSe7KQa5GpCFJKt-pa65oTDrzSy9R2hyNr=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM4a3gHzrPxBuEchmz9Mty5qI4ytDzw2BHhR55y=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMNxVtGF4Ll0rd1cbWT8O_QsoWVIJqxo93ql8sH=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pics>< Response>

<time>1605786989536<//time><rate>5</rate><text>The clear standout of this restaurant is their customer service. Both before and during the pandemic we'd always get complimentary iced tea and small snacks with our orders. One time they even ran out of their normal snacks and gave us a whole bundt cake! That alone keeps me coming back.

I typically order either the dac biet or the thit nuong.  The bread itself has a solid crust but is still soft on the inside. The meat portions are smaller than some other shops but I still think the freebies you get make up for it. Their beef stew is also a solid choice to get.

Give this place a shot if you're in Cypress. The kindness of the owners and the good food will definitely win you over!<//text>< pictures>

This is a place hidden behind plain site across the street from Cypress College. It's a quaint, unassuming little place but it provides wonderful serenity and peace about it. The owners are super wonderful & friendly!!! And of course, the food are very yummy and excellent with a homestyle flare to it. I had the chicken banhmi sandwich and it was bomb! They even gave complimentary iced tea & water while I waited for my order, then, gave my son cookies & mini lollipops when we left. This place is very much like Lee's Sandwiches but provides that feeling like you are eating at grandma's house. The prices are comparable, if not cheaper, than other sandwich places. I highly recommend this wonderful Sandwich House! Yummy!!!</Review>

Fantastic food, super friendly service, what more can you ask for?

< pictures>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPpNW9IoGkclBAquQ3b0VJZZmSGS-U7NM5B7ZKa=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pictures>
<Date>1485480011190< /Date><review>This is going to be a strange way to describe a Vietnamese banhmi shop, but this is not like any other banh mi shop (any that I've been to at least). Upon entering, I was warmly greeted by shop owners Vu and his sister Anne, and the other smiley gentleman who made my sandwich in the kitchen. While Vu was kindly going over the menu with me, I was overcome with a sense of peacefulness.. maybe it was the 4pm sun coming through the windows, the old school purple barstools and purple orchids on every table, or even his white hair which made you feel like you were talking to a wise sage. Anyway, I was already having a good experience just ordering my house special sandwich (#1) when it gets even better! His sister comes out from the back and greets me with a bowl of buttery sugary toast and an iced jasmine tea saying she was so happy that I came and wishing me a happy Vietnamese new year and everything. And even when my sandwich came out, the owner handed it to me with both hands and a small head bow, and let me tell you, if you've never felt this level of kindness and respect from a food joint, you need to come experience this for yourself. And since I wasn't expecting so many goodies, I had so many things to carry, so without hesitation, Anne picked everything up, walked me to my car and opened my door for me! I left feeling so taken care of hahah. And later I found two extra cookies in my bag. Anyway, the sandwich was awesome and I like that you can use your debit card here. I know this review was longer than usual, but I had to share my awesome experience. Much gratitude to Sandwich House, I will definitely be coming back soon.<//review></record>

< Review>
Recently updated to reflect a few recent terrible visits (between 10/01/18 to 12/30/18). Employees have become very rude since I first started coming here earlier in the year. Seem to be more interested in "starting their own brewery" then assisting customers either in person or over the phone (called once to ask to confirm if yeast was in stock and rather then help me the employee insisted I didnt buy my yeast from them rather then answer my question... k?). Seem to always be out of important ingredients, such as most varieties of yeast, and never seem to have the specialty malts I need on-hand. I'll just be going back to Pacific Brewing supplies in San Dimas from now on. Was good while it lasted.</Review>

<username>Daniel Combs</username><Date>1609007759766</Date><Rating>1</Rating>< Review>
I ordered a fork for my bike that on the website  stated it would ship in a couple weeks. My credit card was charged immediately, but I received an email a few hours later explaining the item was out of stock, and would not ship for a couple of months instead of a couple weeks because it was back ordered. I was asked if I wanted to wait, or to be refunded. The following morning I checked their website and it had not been updated, still saying available to ship in a couple weeks. I looked some more around their site hoping to find a suitable replacement. I came across a fork for approximately 25% more, but had a feature I wanted, and to be honest I would have ordered this fork originally had I seen it. This fork is listed as in stock, ready to ship. Now I am happy because things seem like they will work out for the better. I was prepared to pay the difference and have them send me the more expensive fork. Again, I receive an email apologizing, but that fork is also out of stock. She included a link to the only fork they do have in stock for my bike, but the link is to the fork I am trying to replace. I asked for a refund, and received an email almost immediately stating I had been refunded. I checked my credit card acct more than 48 hours later, no pending refund. After another email I am assured the refund was processed, and I should be receiving it shortly, which I did. It seems as if the only part of this operation that runs efficiently is the part that takes your money. As far as keeping items in stock, or at least keeping their website updated is not a priority. Even refunds are at a snails pace, especially when compared to the lightning speed at which your credit card is charged. Never again.</Review>
<pictures>None<//pictures><response>{'time': 1609191411719, 'text': 'Hi Daniel,\n\nThank you for the feedback and we are sorry to hear that you were not happy with your experience.\n\nTo be fair, we are in the middle of a pandemic induced bike boom which has led to product shortages on all bike parts.\n\nFor this reason we put a clearly visible note right next to the "Add to Cart" button that reads: "We are doing our best to keep our inventory current but there may be extended lead times on certain Rockshox suspension, feel free to contact us before purchase for inventory status."\n\nWe are doing our best to update inventory, but forks are selling in such large volumes that it is simply not possible to keep up with the demand.\n\nRegarding the charge and refund procedure, we do agree that our current system isn\'t ideal but this unfortunately is a limitation of the credit card companies. Some online retailers have the ability to simply authorize your card when you place an order and then charge you once it ships. We are unable to do this as authorizations have a limited time frame to them and would therefore make it difficult for us to do pre-orders or backorders.\nYour credit card processor then takes a few days to make the funds available to you. We don\'t agree with this system either, but this is just how online credit processors work.\nPlease let us know if you are still in need of a fork and we will do our best to try and see if we have anything in stock (we have over 70 forks currently in stock) that meets your specs and budget.\n\nThanks,\nPro Bike Supply'}< /response>< Gmap_id>

<Text>These guys hustle so hard. Love the food. Great takeout in bulk too! Highly recommend.<//Text><Pictures>None<//Pictures><Resp>None</Resp><gmapID>0x80dcdf88b07dfec9:0xa77799f18d097019</gmapID></record>

< Review>
THIS. IS. THE. BEST. PLACE. EVER!

This place never disappoints.

SCRATCH THAT.

The only time this place has disappointed me is when it's been CLOSED.

My go-to meal is the chicken combo which normally comes with, shredded chicken, beans, rice, radishes, tortillas, and - if wanted - onions,  and cilantro. Lately, I've been asking for the combos just with the chicken in whole pieces with no beans and double rice. See the Plato de Pollo pic below.

By the way... I am so thankful that I will NEVER have to admit to my late grandfather that I've found a roast chicken that tastes better than his! It is so moist, tender, and flavorful!

And the rice?!?!?!?! Praise him! If I'm running errands, I'll stop in just for an 8 oz. cup - only $2, yall!

Oh, yeah! The combos come with a fountain drink, but only if you

WEAR. A. MASK!<//Review>

< text>
Love this place.  Very unassuming but Wow the food and is good.

I go to El Toro Bravo for 2 different reasons and needs (yes I have food needs 😋):
1. For lunch or dinner and get usual fare: tacos, burritos, tortas etc. and they taste great.
2. Meat by the pound, cooked to perfection.

Case in point...bought a pound of carnitas and one of carne asada for dinner at home with friends.  I also.pixked up some guac and salsa.

Got home, got the tortillas out and the warmer, some cilantro and chopped onions
and made Bueno tacos for the group.

The carnitas is my fav, so juicy and tender...they chop it up before they package it...

Yum, try it out, you won't be dissapointed.</text>

I used to love the other location, stopped in here for some tacos. Ordered chicken enchiladas for my friend. Was told they don’t have enchiladas. It’s on the menu. So I asked for chicken taquitos. <user_name>Savvy Cortez</user_name><time>1516136200965< /time><rate>5</rate>< review>
Excellent service & food!  My husband & I love these smaller Mexican restaurants & this one is our new favorite.  The cook was very accomidating to my nutritional needs (Ketogenic friendly) by creating a burrito bowl for me,  even though it's not on their menu. The carne asada was fantastic & juicy. Not dry at all. My husband got a bean & cheese burrito & was able to add yummy guacamole . He loved his burrito too. Extremely reasonably priced. I eveb have some left overs that I'm looking forward to devouring later. If I could give more stars,  I would.</review>

<rate>5<//rate>< text>
In my review of the El Toro Bravo tortilleria, I gave it a "4" for the food and service but dinged it for the relatively drab location.  Enter their new restaurant a few blocks down the street, which actually has the vibrance that the other location lacks while maintaining the same commitment to service and delicious food.  I'm a hefty dude, and even I get stopped in my tracks by the food portions they offer here and often take home the rest for seconds.  If you get a combo plate (asada, pollo, or carnitas), make sure you buy a bag of chips to go with it - Just makes the experience even better.</text>

< Text>
This was the 1st time I dealt with Portfolio. I was extremely impressed! Customer Sevice Representative JoLynn did a fabulous job explaining to me the cancellation & refund process. She was patient and a total professional. I called because we sold our vehicle and I cancelled the policy with the dealership (as required by the Agreement). The dealership sent me a cancellation acknowledgement but nothing else - no check, no explanation of the process. Just a piece of paper that stated it was an official cancellation notice with a refund amount listed. We had problems with the dealership not being upfront & honest - along with sliding into financing items to which we did not agree. I called the dealership who told me that Portfolio would send them the refund and then they (the dealership) would reimburse us. Portfolio CS representative calmed my fears, she assured me the request had been received and explained the process. She also did a great job explaining how they handle claims - which assured me we had purchased a great product - however, we no longer had the vehicle and asked for the unused portion of the Agreement be refunded. Portfolio took my information and told me to give them a call if I did not receive our refund within 30 days. Portfolio treated me as a very valued customer. In the future BEFORE I buy a new car, I will make sure Portfolio has an agreement with the dealership, and purchase the extended warranty agreement. Just with this interchange I believe Portfolio is a wonderful company, honest and stands by their words & products. I look forward to doing business with them in the future.</Text>

< review>
My 2020 Honda Civic was hit by someone who ran a red light. The Gap insurance didn’t help pay the balance from what I owed after what the insurance paid, (which was surprisingly only about 755 after the last payment I made.) They DID refunded the extended warranty and that is what covered what I owed, NOT Guaranteed Asset Protection. When I called back and asked why, I was told that because of a total loss the GAP was fulfilled. Their contract is such BS!! It is a very shady way to do business. They advertise that they will cover what’s owed in a total loss, but when that accident actually happens you are SOL. Better have that Extended Warranty!

Before getting any type of coverage from them, don’t just look at the google reviews, look at Reddit, look at consumer affairs.com please do your research on them first!!</review>

I had cancelled my extended warranty with Wayne Mazda in early November when I purchased a new car.  I reached out to them several times via email and phone to receive no response.  Frustrated, I called Portfolio (number on the cancellation form).  I spoke with Alesha Hunter. She asked me to email her a copy of my cancellation form.  Within in 24 hours, she was able to inform me that the dealership still hadn't submitted the cancellation to Portfolio.  I then called Mazda to speak with the manager.  Finally, the steps were taken to process my refund.  It is February and I still haven't received my refund.  I emailed Alesha instead of trying the dealership.  She emailed me within the day to tell me the cancellation form had been processed and I should receive a refund.  She was a breath of fresh air.  I really appreciated the fact that Portfolio and Alesha responded to inquiries.  I usually shy away from posting reviews but I gladly volunteered to post this review. <Gmap_id>0x80dce9d156a26883:0x29c8f59112da6c93</Gmap_id><Rate>2</Rate>< Review>
Since I moved from the city in which I purchased my car, finding a service provider in my area that will work with this company has been difficult. It seems they are well known for being difficult. After finding a small shop that is patient enough to attempt the claims process, I find myself waiting over a week to have a claim processed for a repair that is clearly covered by looking at my copy of the agreement, and can be completed within 1 day. After 7 days of hearing nothing from Portfolio, it takes phone calls from both the service provider and myself to have it "expedited" and "sent to management" to be REVIEWED.

I can't imagine why they find it appropriate to keep policy owners without their vehicles for that long. I would have rather they rejected my claim within a reasonable timeframe so that I could have made alternative arrangements with another repair service provider, knowing how difficult that would be. Clearly they are looking for ways to avoid paying for repairs that they agreed to cover rather than working to provide the warranty service that the unfortunate agreement holder paid for.

Anyone considering this company's "service" should look harder for a more reputable 3rd party auto warranty. I give 2 stars only because the people on the phones that have no part in the actual claims process have been generally well-mannered.</Review>

< Text>
I have not had to use my extended warranty with Portfolio but this review is based on the interaction I had with one of their representatives. I spoke with a delightful and very knowledgeable Mrs. JoLynn in the TX office. I called in originally to receive some additional information about the product I was considering purchasing with our new vehicle purchase. The car dealer was unsure of some more specific questions, so I called Portfolio. After going around the phone tree, I ended up speaking Mrs. JoLynn (receptionist at the TX office) who went above and beyond the call of duty to answer all the questions I had about the extended warranty. She was so knowledgeable of the product, explained how the service works, even walked me through hypothetical situations and what the service would look like then. And as if she was reading my mind, told me exactly what page, box number and line item I needed to turn to see this in print on the application from the dealer. Mrs. JoLynn didn't have to take my call and could have sent me back into the phone tree to find a CSR but she didn't. She took the time to make sure I understood fully what I was purchasing and how everything works from start to finish. I ended up purchasing the extended warranty because of her wonderful explanation, her loyalty to the company, and her personal testimony of using the service herself. I understand that someone may rebut with "she has to say that, she works for the company." Allow me to explain; JoLynn exhibited so much class, good character, attention to detail, knowledge, and love for her Lord (let the reader understand), that she would never stick with or work this long for a crooked company. I have no doubt that if I ever do need to utilize this product, I won't have to worry about getting the runaround. Hopefully Portfolio will continue to hire outstanding people like Mrs. JoLynn!</Text>

The room was comfortable enough and was well fitted for the getaway we were on. Cable TV and Wifi were provided, though don't expect to be able to stream movies at night with 1.5mbps download speeds.

The lodge is located only a couple miles from the Sherman Tree and Beetle rock, as well as the Sequoia Museum. The road from the southwest gate to the lodge is a fantastic journey of hairpin turns, incredible views from a height, and breathtaking cliffs without a guardrail for an hour. Fill up your tank before making the drive up!

The food is OK but nothing to write home about at the lodge, in fact, I would recommend to bring some snacks as everything is pricey. Which is to be somewhat expected being in the middle of the park.

The Arts & Crafts/Mission style of the lodge and cabins were very pleasing. Overall I had a very pleasant experience!< /Text></record></dataset><record>

<userid>116565806698673156850< /userid>< name>
Lily Paramaunt</name>
< Time>
1619913079286<//Time>
< rating>
4<//rating>
< Text>
First time to Sequoia Nat'l Park and it's beyond beautiful up here. Wuksachi Lodge is right at the center of all the main attractions and trails so definitely 5 stars for location. There is a lot of signage so it was easy to find. Because the Lodge is in the middle of the forest you see a ton of wildlife without even trying which is fantastic. The only down side is that it's the only place with a restaurant in all of Sequoia Nat'l Forest I believe so you have to eat at the Waksuchi Lodge restaurant. The food is pricey but really good. I was pleasantly surprised at the options, portion size and quality of the meals. There's a mini fridge in the room so definitely bring your own drinks and snacks. You can find other food options at the town at the base of the mountain called Three Rivers but it's about an hour drive from Waksuchi through winding mountain roads so a pain to go just for lunch or dinner.  The staff is super friendly and welcoming and really love the diversity of guests staying here. We stayed in a two queen room and it's very spacious with a small table with 3 chairs, closet, bench by the door to take dirty boots/clothes off, and average size bathroom.<//Text>

< Text>
Brett completely turned this trip around for my fiance and me! <userid>117832408789555351833</userid><username>BradJill<//username>< date>
1558568908651<//date>
<Rating>3< /Rating>< text>
We recently spent two nights at the Wuksachi Lodge in Sequoia National Park. This is the feature park lodge excellently located just a few miles from major sightseeing in the Giant Forest section of the park.

Reservation was made 6 months in advance directly through the park website. Email confirmation was received immediately. 4pm Check-in at the main lodge was very slow, around 30 minutes due to two sets of guest ahead of us in the queue. Hopefully they will learn to check in guests quicker in the future.

Lobby area is nice, includes seating near a stone fireplace. There is a gift shop on site as well as a restaurant called the Peak. We had dinner here one night, it was quite poor (see separate review) so we opted to not eat here the next day.

Rooms are found in 3 separate buildings around 400 metres from the lodge. There is a carpark below. You have take your luggage rather far to get into the building and then up to your rooms. Rooms were decent but not what you'd expect for the room rates normally.

Space was good, furnishing a bit dated and decor common. Bed comfort just ok. Room came with sitting sofa and chair, desk with chair, fridge, flat screen TV and enough closet space for most. Bathroom space was fine, shower water pressure a bit weak but plenty of warm water. We paid higher rate for a room with a view. Our room was a first floor room overlooking the carpark. That felt like a wasted spend.

Overall, you are paying for the location with Wuksachi Lodge. We very much appreciated being so close to the Giant Forest, allowing us to visit early in the morning before too many tourists overwhelmed the trails and sights. It was nice being able to return to the lodge for a bit of a rest before heading back out midday. Otherwise, we felt rather meh about the room considering the high rates and would probably opt to stay elsewhere and just drive in for sightseeing next time.< /text>

<Text>Great place to go up and see snow during the winter months. Tons of hiking trails close to the lodge and several of the largest trees in the world. Loved our New Years stay here & would definitely stay here again! The restaurant is excellent & reasonably priced. Beautiful views from the dining room. The hotel staff was very friendly & helpful. The room was very comfortable & nice. Not super luxurious but it’s 7500 up in a National Park. The only complaint is that I upgraded at the last minute to a Deluxe ‘View’ room & there was a tree in front of the window so I couldn’t really see the mountains. It was a nice view but I expected a better view for the $25 upgrade. The rooms accommodate a family of 5 which is great. Can’t wait to come back!<//review>

1545264926320< /date>
<rate>3</rate>< Text>
Wintertime visit - Upon arrival already tired from the long day of hiking didn’t realize the rooms were separate from the rest of the lodge. Lodge had a nice cozy fireplace with great Christmas decorations! Bar had great wings and draft beer! Definitely check the bar out. Excluding the bartender the customer service wasn’t the greatest, the wait staff seemed unorganized and all over the place. The rooms are divided into 3 different buildings, parking is pretty far from the actual entrance, you rely on a baggage cart to haul your items to your room. The path to the rooms were icy and snowy, not well cleared off. Not to mention the buildings with rooms had 3 floors with no elevators so that’s inconvenient. The room didn’t have a microwave which made things difficult for people who food prep vs expensive restaurant. It wasn’t worth the $225 we paid. BUT it wasn’t a bad stay - ended up having a very relaxing night in a beautiful area! This lodge is very convenient as far as location!</Text>

<Review>The best accommodation in California! We have been travelling throughout CA and stayed in multiple hotels and Wuksachi Lodge is by far the best place we have stayed on our journey! Please do not be put off by the Government Shutdown, the Sequoa Park is still open. From the moment we walked through the lobby, a woody scent filled the air followed by the warmest of welcome from the chap on the reception desk. Following check in we passed the log fire burning in the lobby to the restaurant for lunch. Home made sweet potato and curry soup, views of the beautiful trees covered in snow out the window and a hot chocolate, bliss. As for our room, the bed was so comfortable, incredible view, warm, very clean and the soaps in the bathroom are of high quality. Highly recommended this gem of a place! Breakfast, lunch and dinner has also been the best selection of food we have had on our trip!! Hats off to the chef and all the friendly staff, you are doing an incredible job!!< /Review>< user_name>

<rating>5<//rating><review>A wonderful place to stay while visiting Sequoia National Park and seeing the Trees, doings some hikes, and visiting Kings canyon. My wife and I stayed here for 3-4 nights and I will not complain. We came May 7th, 2019 - May 10th, 2019

This place has the antique feel of an original lodge built in the mountains and is ran professionally.

The staff is friendly, the beds are comfortable from the sheets and pillows down to the softness/hardness of the mattress was to our liking. We felt like a king and queen sleeping on it and had good nights sleep every night. You may want earplugs when you sleep as people can be heard in the hallways if they're walking by and talking or closing doors somewhat loudly.

We didn't eat lunch there but had the all you can eat breakfast every morning and had dinner there 3 nights in a row.

The breakfast is decent for the price and the dinner is high quality but you will pay the price for it. Servers were excellent and friendly.
Breakfast is around $15-$20 per person and dinner is around $35-$50 if you are drinking alcohol.

They have a gift shop with everything you may need in case you forget something like snacks or chap stick etc.

Their dining room is open and makes you feel grand.

It's a good place that you should stay at if you want to remember yourself having a great time. Visit this place if you can or skip the hotel and just check out the trees.</review><pictures>None<//pictures>< Resp>
{'time': 1559075899684, 'text': 'Thank you Nate for your wonderful review. We are pleased to hear that you slept comfortably as a King and Queen should. We hope that someday you will return to allow us another opportunity to impress you.'}< /Resp>

<Name>Will Rodes<//Name><Time>1559845957621</Time>< rate>
1<//rate>
< Text>
I had high hopes of what our time would be at the Wuksachi lodge. It was an experience that we splurged on and thought that it would enhance our enjoyment of Sequoia National Park. It was actually quite the opposite. The room was over 80 degrees when we arrived. The maintenance man came out after two calls about it. He turned off the wall units, but this still did not cool our "Superior" room below 75º F even with the windows open. I have never seen a baby pack-n-play as cheap as the one that was given for my daughter to sleep in. You could literally feel the bars through the mattress in it.

The Peak restaurant was the single largest disappointment. It is everything you would expect from a vendor that has a monopoly. The food was of terrible quality for the prices. The burger I ordered the first night was not cooked to temperature. The restaurant was out of milk at breakfast the first morning, meaning we could not give my one year old daughter milk. The kid's spaghetti that my kids ordered the second night made them both sick. The last morning we were there, they were literally running out of everything to the point where you had to ask the wait staff for each item. The only server that was helpful was Trevor.

I would not recommend the Wuksachi Lodge or the Peak Restaurant to anyone. You would be better off staying and eating outside of the park.

The Lodge sent me a survey after our trip which I gave them the same feedback as posted above and asked to be contacted. 6 weeks have passed and I still have not received a call.<//Text>

< Review>
The Wuksachi Lodge had a delicious restaurant inside, a small gift shop, and a comfortable seating area. The rooms are a short drive away, and boy are they pretty. The beds are comfy, the bathroom is clean, and you don't feel like you're on top of each other. But the views are really what elevate these rooms. I can't imagine there is a room in that lodge with a bad view. We were surrounded by trees, and you just felt so in touch with the park, despite being in a very comfortable bed. The breakfast was a buffet, and while it wasn't cheep, it was delicious! I ate so much it was crazy. I could write a whole separate post on the parks themselves. They are some of my favorite places in the world. So many different features all in one place, it's incredible. Plus the lodge offers a free shuttle all through these wonderful works of nature. This is a wonderful experience. You must must MUST book your room well in advance, sometimes a year out. But I promise it's worth it.<//Review>

<Resp>None</Resp>< UserId.>
None<//UserId.>
<Review>You couldnt ask for a better location in Sequoia than Wuksachi Lodge. Located 2 miles from Lodgepole (which is where they have a marketplace, grill, and the shuttle for the other Sequoia attractions), Wuksachi is right where you want to be located in the park. The lodge itself and the room was clean, but unfortunately when we were there in July 2018, they were under construction on the grounds, both in front of the lodge and next to the dining room. This really takes away from the experience, and I was surprised they were doing the work during peak season? The lodge itself has very little when it comes to amenities. There is a restaurant on site that actually had great food at a mid-level price. The downside is you need to book reservations for dinner, so unless you get them in early, you will find yourself eating at either 5:00 or 8:00. There is not much else to do at the lodge. No pool or game room or anything like that. That may not be an issue for most since the main reason to visit Sequoia is to be in the park, but for people who like to break up their adventures with a day at the resort, there is nothing to do at this one. They did have a nice stargazing retreat at night which was provided free of cost, and that was a lot of fun. In terms of the rooms, be aware that they do not have A/C, just window and ceiling fans. Since it was Summer when we were at the lodge, it was pretty warm during the day and the room was stuffy. Thankfully it cooled down enough at night.<//Review>< pics>
None< /pics>

< text>
Mostly better than average national park lodging. But, having to carry all personal items including coolers (because of bears) was a real bummer because rooms are far from parking lots and up on the hill.

Also, lack of an AC unit was harder to deal with than I thought. Even after opening all windows and turning on all the fans at max speed for 2+ hours before sleep, I had some trouble getting asleep because the room was too hot.

All the staffs I interacted with were very friendly and professional.<//text>

This is a very decent lodge.  It's not gigantic, it's not part of a village, and there is no night (or day-life) here.  It is very quiet, very clean and well kept with a well placed restaurant. <user_id>101451251457664323968<//user_id>< name>
Beryl Reid<//name>
< Date>
1446488849481< /Date>
<Rate>4</Rate>< Review>
We stayed one night. The main Lodge is nice, with a warm fire and nice restaurant. It's fairly new and is very "mountain lodge" in decor - rustic and comfortable. The actual rooms are in three separate buildings. The location of the rooms could be a problem for people with disabilities ( not a problem for us) but if I had trouble with a lot of walking and some uphill walkways, it wouldn't be good. The rooms were clean, no wifi in rooms, but you could get it in the main Lodge building. The location is in one of the most beautiful places on the earth, so that is biggest plus, in my opinion. Meals were not included, so consider that when booking. The only place to eat ( breakfast, lunch or dinner) is at the restaurant in main Lodge building. Full breakfast was around $14, continental was $8. We had dinner in restaurant. The food was very good at average-high price. It has to be trucked in over hairy mountain roads, so I'm sure that is reason for prices.<//Review>

<time>1465311826044< /time>< Review>
I give Wuksachi Lodge a 5 star because of the amazing service and kindness of the workers.

--So I brought my brand new Canon Rebel t5i to take photos and videos on in Sequoia National Park because it is spectacularly beautiful! But, this was a very brand new Camera, like I got it only a week ago and I bought it from my uncle and he gave me some other cool gear with it too, including a charger. Unfortunately, it was the wrong charger for my camera. So toward the end of the first day our of three day trip, I was devastated because my camera was on low battery and I was going to not be able to film and photograph the rest of the trip. HOWEVER, I asked the workers at the front desk if any of them had a spare charger and they thought of all their coworkers who had cameras. Eventually, one of the coworkers had the exact same camera and the right charger and she let me use hers. Her name was Victoria Dunbar and she even insisted on letting me bring HER charger back to my room to charge my camera for the duration of my stay!

The views from where we stayed are also incredible and the bedroom was very big and spacious. The cots they have are also the best cots I have ever slept on!

By and large, fabulously friendly staff.</Review>

<user_id>111423885386510908084<//user_id>< Name>
Casey DuPont</Name>
<Date>1539408731918<//Date><rate>4</rate>< text>
Wuksachi is located at the top of Sequoia NP, close to the sequoia groves an King's Canyon NP. It is a unique setup, the main common area of front desk and restaurant is separate (a short 5 minute walk) from all the rooms. The restaurant, gift shop, heated deck, and front desk have a mountain Lodge setting and mountain view. The room accommodation portion of Wuksachi is more of a very basic hotel. The room provides basic beds, a small fridge, small TV, and and attached bathroom. While it meets all needs, I believe the rooms were overpriced and the room buildings require some renovations. Do not expect anything like a Lodge.<//text>

<UserId.>108462668052746752468< /UserId.>< user_name>
Wyndham Messinger</user_name>
<date>1543962812080< /date><Rate>5<//Rate>< text>
We went up for a few days and had a nice stay in the snow. The hotel was well staffed although they all insist on calling you Mr and Mrs, which I found a bit too formal for my liking. The restaurant had quite a selection for being in such a remote area and the bartender was fun to talk to. The drinks they made really fit the weather. Speaking of which, if you intend to go up during snow season, be sure you buy snow chains and learn how to put them on BEFORE you make the drive. Many people got into minor accidents or had no idea how to put on chains when they needed to. Lucky many of the people there will help you out, if you don't run into anyone and you can't put on your chains, you might be stuck for several hours like some of the folks I met.</text>

<rating>1</rating>< Review>
Wuksachi Lodge will over book!  How do I know, we booked, gave the credit card, got the confirmation and started on the way up the hill. This was a direct reservation no 3rd party was used. When we talked with them they stated they don't use any 3rd party sites.  Note this place is in the park so you must pay a fee to get to it. What made me more fired up was the screen I could see they had over booked people the next two days, too. They had no place for us to go except to spend an hour and half going back down to three rivers out of the park.  Book at your own risk! It's my understanding this is owned by the Delaware North Company (DNC) who also has the market next door while trying to find if a camping option could work. One star is as low as it will let me go but it should have no stars. If you had the same issue please let people know, it's a long way to go without another option. #WillOverBook #Hotel #WuksachiLodge< /Review>
< Pictures>
None</Pictures>
< Response>
{'time': 1565731220765, 'text': "We apologize for the inconvenience that you suffered. We do use 3rd party bookings and this is why we can get overbooked. We offer rooms from our inventory to all of Expedia partners and also have our own Central Reservation System. These sources will cause us to be overbooked in our system and is something that every hotel deals with and its not exclusive to Wuksachi Lodge. We do our best to be ahead of it but it doesn't always get resolved before the guest arrives. We hope that the accommodations that we secured for you was acceptable and that you were able to enjoy the park."}</Response>

<Rating>5< /Rating>< text>
I'm writing this primarily to tie-up a many-month feedback lapse: One of the lodge employees, with a name-tag denoting Josil, very kindly provided my wife and I a set of lengthy explanations to a long list of inquiries. A lot of detail garnered from her personal experiences helped us significantly. This was while we were staying at the lodge where where she worked as a receptionist, not the restaurant-portion.

However, in coming here I've seen a perplexing mix of restaurant reviews. There must be some variability in chefs! To provide our tip on that balance - the restaurant was fantastic. The portions were large - much larger than expected! Very pleasing when you've been traipsing about the Sequoias all day. (Also worth noting - they provided gluten-free options, a must for my wife.)  The workload on the wait-staff was quite high, but provided great service despite this. Equally important, the ambiance of the place was lovely and perfectly suited the external environs/views thereof. A high-ceiling open space, stone slab and timber construction, centered on a large, radiant fireplace.<//text>

< Date>
1561429582883</Date>
<review>A charming lodge in the beautiful Sequoia NP. Beds were a bit on the firm side and could use more pillows. Staff was friendly and helpful in navigating us to areas of the park. Nothing beats stepping out of your hotel room to a gorgeous mountain view.

Some things to note:
- The path from the check in area to the three lodges isn't particularly well lit. Make sure to bring a flashlight when walking about at night.
- When you access the Sequoia set of rooms, there are a set of shallow, uneven stairs with no handrail. However, there is a ramp which makes for a much smoother walk.
- The front desk fails to mention this, but it is on the check in materials that a bellhop can bring your luggage to your room. You can also get a luggage cart in your lodge "house" and wheel it down to the car.
- There is no pool. Believe it or not, someone asked the bartender if there was a pool. No, but there are streams and lakes.
- Be prepared to disconnect from your cellphone. Wifi is often spotty and cellular service is practically nonexistent.

Meals are not included with the room rate. The buffet breakfast that is in the restaurant adjoining the check-in area of the lodge is average and I don't feel it is worth the $16-20 unless you eat more than one plate of food. (The prices for the buffet vary based on whether you get the cold or hot breakfast, and the price seems to vary based on whether it is the week or weekend, and the time of year you visit.) It is a typical "American" breakfast of potatoes, bacon, sausage, scrambled eggs, pancakes, pastries, toast, bagels, cereal, some fruit, and oatmeal. There isn't anything special about the breakfast. The pizza from the restaurant, however, is delicious. So are most of the dishes served for lunch and dinner.<//review>< UserId.>

<Name>Nicholas Graham<//Name><userid>105636172378498418045< /userid>< text>
The service at the restaurant is slow and disorganized. Be prepared to wait an hour even for a simple sandwich! However, the atmosphere is amazing, with gorgeous views of the mountains, so the wait can be bearable with good company, an appetizer and some drinks.

The food is fresh and relatively healthy for a restaurant, with vegan and vegetarian options available. While the food isn't amazing on its own, for the elevation at 2000m+ (7000ft+) above sea level, the quality is amazing.<//text>

<Review>Staying inside the park was perfect. But overall the lodgings are not great value for money.Staff in the lodge reception were a bit clueless. We asked for some basic advice about where to park for seeing some highlights in the park and the need for snow chains and reception staff didn’t seem to know much.The lodging is in a separate building which is fine. A bit like a motel in the middle of the woods. Plenty of parking. Half of the rooms are on the 2nd floor with no elevator. We were lucky to get a 1st floor room so we didn’t have to carry luggage up. Plenty warm enough even in snowy, cold conditions and clean enough.Your only food option is the restaurant in the lodge which gets booked up so make sure to reserve when you arrive. The restaurant is ok but not amazing.< /Review>< Pictures>

< review>
We came in early April and the place was still mostly snowed in. The lodge and the rooms are a couple of hundred meters apart. The rooms themselves are the standard hotel fair, but take heed that there are no elevators, so if you are on the second or third floor you will have to carry your luggage (if you have any) up the long walkway from the car parking to the building and then up the stairs.
In the end, the place is amazing since it is in an amazing place.< /review>

<text>We stayed here for one night on the weekend in mid December. The Superior room was large and clean. If you bring children, definitely book this room. The atmosphere was spectacular! The short walk to the main lodge for dinner was great! We had an amazing dinner and the service was excellent (except the bar tender was quite slow). There was few feet of snow in the surrounding area but the walkways were shoveled and clear. I recommend you bring a good flashlight if you plan on walking out of your room after dark, the hotel does provide one but it isn't that great. Overall, I highly recommend this Lodge to stay!< /text>< Pictures>

We loved our stay, the superior suites were very nice! There were a few surprises, which were inconvenient. I did not realize that the lodge was made up of multiple buildings. It was a bit of a pain to lug all our gear and kids up the snowy paths to the rooms. <Text>Stayed at this hidden gem 12/12-14.  Its nice to have a decent place to stay at within a national park.  HOWEVER, they decided to perform some upkeeps to the lodges; although it makes complete sense to do this during off peak season, they have failed to 1. have any warnings chemicals will be used; such as paint thinners2. NO ventilation where areas of chemicals are used - windows kept closed in the halls and doors also closed3.  starting the construction at 8:30AM4. Failed to place all guests in 1/3 or 2/3 lodges and work on one lodge at a time5. upon expressing a complaint at check out (after having headaches, nausea, and swollen eyes/face due to the chemicals) everyone whom I talked to from the front desk to the executive chef of the lodge were extremely nice ...EXCEPT the manager.  I left my number and email for the manager to reach me.  I waited long enough in the lobby to have the chance to speak with him, but he was in a meeting.  WHICH WAS FINE, but he should have contacted me.  It has now been over 48 hours since I left the premise and I have yet to hear from management.This is simply a case of gross negligence.  Its a beautiful get-away to enjoy mother nature.  The last thing I had expected was to be sleeping with fumes the whole night that resulted in severe discomfort for me and my pups.  Any time they passed the halls, they sneezed.  I do not wish this kind of experience on anyone, especially at a national park.</Text><Response>None<//Response><user>None</user><Gmap_id>0x80955e7bbfa947a1:0x569f3289d86ec019< /Gmap_id>< Pics>

<user_name>Paul Vasquez<//user_name><Date>1345654710439<//Date><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< rating>

<UserId.>111428638507422761457< /UserId.><gmap_id>0x80955e7bbfa947a1:0x569f3289d86ec019< /gmap_id><response>None< /response>< text>
I'm writing this review only on the restaurant, at which my wife and I ate twice during our vacation in Sequoia National Park.

The food was pricey, as I would expect from any restaurant in such a unique location, but I didn't feel it was bad quality. My wife and I both enjoyed what we ordered. I ordered the turkey burger both days, and my wife ordered the prime rib sandwich. I will say that it wasn't any more expensive than the Grant's Grove restaurant, however. If you want to eat "real" food (by that I mean, not junk food) in the Sequoia park, these are your only two options.

I can corroborate a previous statement that we were told dinners were by reservation only; however, we went back to the lodge later to use the facilities, and I asked if they had any dinner openings, and I was told enthusiastically that they did, and from what I could tell, the dinning room was veritably empty.</text>

< username>
Dallas Fonseca</username>
<Rate>5</Rate></record></dataset><record>
< text>
Picture-window vistas of the sequoias and a muted Indian theme in the decor, with an unexpected Japanese touch in the interesting earthenware dishes. Menu has that depressingly burger-centric mix familiar from American ski resorts. A Martian would come away innocent of the knowledge that this restaurant is perched above the preeminent fruit-and-vegetable-growing region of North America, such is the generic, corporate feel of the menu.

Service on my visit was slipshod, with a fifteen-minute wait to order. A competent salmon sandwich arrived with fries which a charitable soul would describe as lukewarm.

A prime location suffering from the slackness bred of monopoly, I suspect.</text>

<Rate>4</Rate><Time>1531366188558< /Time><name>Shane Wood</name>< review>
Check-in personnel need to know and share more info about shuttle service. We learned more by overhearing another's conversation. The staff was never rude or mean just not as knowledgeable as we expected. Clean room, hot water was extremely hot and was at times too hot. The room had a fridge but no microwave. The fridge's thermostat was buried under the 'freezer' section's ice and as such it never got the fridge section nicely cold because it always thought it was cold enough. We appreciated the shuttle service but two drvers we had were very curt while another driver was very friendly and helpful. Most shuttle rides were very crowded and we would've done more driving if parking was more generous. The lodge restaurant had, at best, reasonable food but was overpriced and not worth the cost. Given another chance we would buy our food from the lodgepole market (2 miles away) and prepare sandwiches ourselves. Example: day one we bought an $8 burger (from the children's menu) that was worth $16, but on day two we paid $18 for a bison burger which we never want to eat again. The fresh fruit, available at every meal we ate, was always very good but repetitive (pineapple, cantelope, and honeydew). The meal portions we're good. The four stars were mainly due to location and condition of the hotel. It was in a beautiful place and hard to not appreciate the view. Being located within the park saved us an hour plus (minimum) drive each day to reach the sights. We would recommend the lodge and, if we go back, we will stay there again.< /review>

<userid>111178993691807272573<//userid><username>Rich Kapp< /username><time>1520889387649<//time>< rating>
4< /rating>
< review>
I really feel this place does a much better job than what I received. There were a lot of headaches in the beginning, but management straightened everything out. The room was clean, the dinner staff was exceptionally friendly and easy-going, and one can not complain about the easy access to the national and state parks. Had it not been for Mr. J, I would have left a 1-star review and a much longer description.

A few side-notes: Dinner is a bit over-priced, they should have wild-caught fish at those price points. I had a couple whiskey-doubles (Glenlivet & Chivas) which put me back 45 bucks, felt like I was at a freaking night-club in San Fran.

Make sure you know whether or not the roads are open via the route you plan to take in. They may close the northern route because of snow and it will suck to have to go ALL the way around (+4 hours minimum).

The team knows the wifi situation is no good. That being said, after speaking with management, the fix they were in the final stages of implementing should solve a lot of problems, looks like I just came on the wrong day. Ignore bad WIFI comments before today's date. If bad WIFI comments persist after March 15 or so, I'd say their solution was no good and they have to continue working on it.

Hope this helps someone!</review>

< userid>
109732257589717563401< /userid>
< Name>
J V< /Name>
< Date>
1519253386025<//Date>
<rate>1< /rate>< Review>
Due to the many highly rated reviews, I was expecting more than what I paid for. $230 as a discounted AAA rate isn't peanuts, and for that price I was expecting a resort and not a motel.

First, there is no parking directly in front of the reception for guest to quickly check in. You would still have to park in the parking lot and run to the lobby to check in. I guess I didn't look as good as the previous guest, because I didn't get my room upgraded. Hotel staff greeted me and gave me some brief information to get my stay started.

Upon getting to the rooms, I had to park in a no parking zone to get my bags out. Though there were many luggage carts, there were no attendants to help unload and transport to the room. Baggage was then lugged to the second story up the stairs due to the lack of elevator.

The room was about the same size as an average yet dated Hampton inn with far less amenities. No microwave, no DVD player, different colored bulbs (maybe it's just a pet peeve of mine), each bed had only two small and flat pillows each, linen was pretty rough, and the comforter had stains on them. Corners, curtains, and ceiling fan were dusty and had cob webs. Tub was cracked, tub spout would not operate properly when attempting to switch to the shower head and the shower head was weak and seemed to not operate properly as well. Shower had a soap dispenser, yet you had your choice of lime scented shampoo or lime scented shampoo. The toilet flushed like it was made by NASA and required 300 psi to propel your flush into space (sorry I'll leave the jokes out) it was loud.

The walls are pretty thin and the hotel allows pets. The WiFi is only mediocre in the lobby and pretty much non existent in the rooms. Vending machine was down and there were no other community amenities near the rooms.

For the price I'd expect at least a continental breakfast and due to the lack of activities available at the lodge, there could have been complimentary sack lunches as well (Hampton inn does this free of charge).

I guess I was expecting a camp lodge experience with campfires going to enjoy, s'mores,  and a friendly old bearded guy playing campfire songs for the guests. After all, the experience of seeing the Sequoia are a once in a lifetime experience, and I was hoping the lodging would be as well.

Lastly, if you book online you will be charged a deposit (equivalent to a one night stay), when you check out, the entire bill will be charged to your card. If you used a credit card the deposit will be credited back to your account in a couple days, if debit, 7-30 days depending on your bank.

It is apparent that businesses in these rare locations do not place customer service high on their agenda. Where else would you stay and eat so close to the Sequoia? And I guess this is why they don't have to strive so hard as other competitors.

I'm new at this review thing, though it is well overdue, customer service in this country is not what it used to be. I am not one of those guys that gives jiffy lube coffee a five star rating, and neither should the reviewers (no offense to jiffy lube coffee).

To prove my point, at the end of my stay I was greeted with my bill at the lobby and was not asked how my stay was. Not one to split hairs, but it would have been nice to be asked. Sorry wuksachi lodge, it wasn't worth the visit.

Thank you owner for acknowledging my experience, I post not only to help your business grow but to allow business owners the ability to improve and keep an edge on the corporate conglomerates that corner each market. In any business, customer experience and service should be the corner Stone to any business. Without the customer, there would be no business. The location of your lodge is in a beautiful area and I wish the best of business for you in the future! Regards JV< /Review>

<Rating>2</Rating>< Review>
The pizza was good, however, once we had ordered the pizza, we were told to take it back to our room, at the time there was a couple eating pizza right where we wanted to eat it and the previous night, there were 5+ people eating pizza and other meals there. We asked why they were allowed and we were not and they simply said "they were misinformed". After a fair bit of reasoning, they let us stay and eat it there. There is nothing at the bar where the pizza is ordered telling you you must take it back to your room implying you could eat it there so something as simple as a sign saying "all food must be consumed elsewhere" or something along those lines would let people with the intentions of eating there let them know they can't.

The previous night, we went into the restaurant which seemed nice but, they had a very small menu. We ordered the food and it didn't come out quite right, 2 of the 4 dishes we ordered tasted both stale and burnt unfortunately.

Besides the fact that the room's furniture was dated and the linens had hair on them (white sheets and bedding would be a nice change and would improve the room), the staff were friendly and they would do what they could to help, especially the people at the reception desk< /Review>

<username>Nikolai Pitchforth</username><date>1511744763551<//date><rate>3</rate>< Review>
Not a lot of options to stay in the park. Lodge is adequate but not quite what the website implies. The "lodge" is cosy but the rooms are not in that building, they are a few minutes away. Room was somewhat dated and had a weird smell. Rollaway beds and cardboard boxes lined the hallway, felt like a storage area. They make you sign a disclaimer to accept that the WiFi is poor... they should tell you before you book that it's unusable (we were relying on it to plan our itinerary). There is one restaurant, food was mixed quality (corn chowder great, potatoes among the worst I've eaten) but those who didn't make a reservation waited a while. It's nice to wake up in the forest and the price was ok compared to other national park hotels but we wouldn't rush back.< /Review>

The restraunt at the lodge leaves much to be desired. The wait staff left us without water numerous times and at 5pm, were out of quite a few entree choices on the menu. We enjoyed the views here, but began to loathe dining in the restaurant every night. The dinner options were overpriced, whilr vegetarian and gluten free options were limited mostly to salads. I do not recommend the vegetarian burger or "field roast". Wi-Fi here is the slowest I have experineced. Staying in the lodge was fine, but our room had no air conditioning and no elevator. It was clean and adequate for our stay with lots of wildlife right outside our door. Deer and bears were seen by members in our party.<//review>

< user>
105085691299235356893< /user>
< name>
David McCarty< /name>
<Date>1468737794497</Date><rating>3<//rating><review>There is no A/C. At night it gets cool enough that this isn't a major problem, but I still wished for it once or twice. You will have no cell coverage at all - phone, texting, data - nothing. That's true in pretty much the whole park, so nothing against the hotel, but be aware that their wifi is abysmal, so while, yes, you CAN get SOME things online, be sure to have downloaded all your maps, audio books, guides, and whatever else you were planning on using while you were here BEFORE you come. Again, the hotel probably can't get anything better, so this is more of a warning than a complaint. TIP: if you are coming as a group, consider getting long-range walkie talkies or something like that.

The water comes out of the tap at a VERY slow rate - 28.8 ml / second or .46 gallons / minute. I understand the need to conserve water, but it shouldn't take a full minute to fill up 2 water bottles.

My door didn't close all the way unless you pulled on it, which in and of itself wasn't a big deal, but lent to the general feeling that this building is older and could use a bit of a freshening up, although I acknowledge that some may find it more of a charming, quaint sort of feel and prefer it that way.

As far as I could tell, the only difference bergen the standard and deluxe rooms was that the more expensive ones are ever so slightly bigger and have a chair. Big woop - I recommend the cheaper room unless you have a need for a few extra square feet of space.

You must walk a short distance from the car to your room. Some may like the feeling of remoteness that this gives, but it isn't particularly handicap-friendly, if that's an issue for you.

The beds were comfortable, the rooms were clean, and the location was fantastic. Really, when you get right down to it, that's all that really matters, right?</review>< pictures>
None<//pictures>

< userid>
105101135315891932705<//userid>
< name>
Sean McG. Powell< /name>
< review>
I stayed here because of its proximity to the Giant Forest at Sequoia.  There are actually no giant sequoias that I saw in the lodge area--you need to drive a few minutes down the road.  The room I stayed in was nice.  It had no air conditioning--just a window fan--but a/c wasn't needed during my stay in early August, as daytime highs were only in the low 70's.  WiFi was extremely slow, but free.  There's no cell phone signal here as of the time of this review, so you really need the WiFi if you feel the need to be connected to the outside world.  The lodge's restaurant--The Pines--was adequate (not fantastic), and the bottled beers quite expensive.  The all-you-can eat barbecue dinner at nearby Wolverton was a nice change.  Overall, a perfectly enjoyable stay.<//review>

<Review>This not Giant Forest Lodge.
It is a place to stay in Sequoia.
I found that I could rent a small RV for what they charge to stay here. Next time I will rent the RV and stay at Lodge pole. WL is pleasent enough, but the design of separate lodging buildings from lobby and reasturant make it feel like no architect was used. You cannot drive up to the front door to check in. The long paths to the lodging buildings are poorly maintained. Be prepared to lug your bags up and down stairs. Rooms could have had balconies to enjoy the lodge pole forest but the design doesn't understand that we are here to be involved with nature. The real shocker was the notice that the water does not meet California standards. Breakfast buffett was executed poorly. The food was often cold and dishes not available to serve ones self. Tables and chairs were crammed in so guests often were bumping into seated dinners.
The wifi worked well in my room, but that's not why I am here.
The beds are soft and they have no backboards.
Got rained out of Ranger talk at lodge pole and came back to dine early.  Even though there were open tables I was told I had to wait. When seated, got bread with oil but no vinigar.  Getting hot water refills while waiting for dinner was difficult.  It took 50 minutes for food to arrive.  My wife got plain dried out and cold rice instead of what was ordered.  The whole operation with armature and inefficient.  Definatly a disappointment at high prices

(Translated by Google) We had a great time. The beauty of the park around it was amplified by a very strong snowfall of the days before which made everything even more beautiful. The structure is warm and welcoming. Our room was clean and large with a nice window facing the snowy forest upstream. I believe, given the fact that there are not many structures in the area, that it is advisable to book early ... if you have already decided a date ... certainly covid permitting.

(Original)
Siamo stati benissimo. La bellezza del parco intorno è stata amplificata da una fortissima nevicata dei giorni prima che hanno reso il tutto ancora più bello. La struttura è calda e accogliente. La nostra stanza era pulita e grande con un bella finestra verso sul bosco innevato a monte. Credo, considerato il fatto che non sono molte le strutture in zona, che sia consigliabile prenotare per tempo...se avete già deciso una data...certo covid permettendo.< /review>

< Review>
(Translated by Google) The Wuksachi Lodge unfortunately lives alone on their location. The reception was surprisingly unfriendly and they frittered you off hectic. The room was ok, but not very clean (hair on the pillows, carpet dirty). Nice was the towel, which was folded into a bear and positioned on one of the beds. Amazingly bad is the in-house restaurant: of five dishes was a cold, one was totally over-salted and was also charged too expensive. And that anyway already "salted" prices. Not surprisingly, meals went back at many tables. Only the dessert was convincing, but the service was poor: drinks were forgotten and complaints were hardly received. When we then refrained from tipping was actually asked how much tip we want to give. When we explained our intention to give none, we were briskly finished. Overall, I advise the accommodation conditionally, the food but definitely to alternatives. 2 stars only for the location and because the accommodation is basically ok.

(Original)
Die Wuksachi Lodge lebt leider allein von ihrer Lage. Der Empfang war erstaunlich unfreundlich und man wurde hektisch abgefrühstückt. Das Zimmer war ok, aber nicht ganz sauber (Haare auf den Kopfkissen, Teppichboden dreckig). Nett war das Handtuch, das zu einem Bären gefaltet und auf einem der Betten positioniert war. Erstaunlich schlecht ist das hauseigene Restaurant: von fünf Speisen wurde eine kalt serviert, eine war total versalzen und wurde auch noch zu teuer abgerechnet. Und das bei sowieso schon "gesalzenen" Preisen. Nicht verwunderlich, dass Speisen an vielen Tischen zurück gingen. Einzig der Nachtisch konnte überzeugen, jedoch war auch der Service mangelhaft: Getränke wurden vergessen und auf Beanstandungen kaum eingegangen. Als wir dann davon abgesehen haben Trinkgeld zu geben wurde tatsächlich nachgefragt wie viel Trinkgeld wir denn geben wollen. Als wir unsere Absicht keines zu geben erläuterten wurden wir forsch zu Ende bedient. Insgesamt rate ich bei der Unterkunft bedingt, beim Essen aber auf jeden Fall zu Alternativen. 2 Sterne nur für die Lage und weil die Unterkunft grundsätzlich in Ordnung ist.<//Review>

<review>(Translated by Google) We had the expectations of a rustic, clean mountain hotel by the previous stay in the Tenaya Lodge. What Wuksachi offers, however, are by European standards a maximum of 2 stars, but all for a (European imaginary price for 4-5 stars) The reception was cold, stressed and unfriendly. The houses are relatively far away from the lodge itself. The hallways of the houses do not give the impression that they are cleaned on a regular basis. The same goes for the rooms and especially for the windows. The bathrooms are ugly and unkempt with plastic shower trays. Breakfast was ok, but served in a (very) cold dining room. I would book the next visit a hotel in the valley and for the long journey in purchase.

(Original)
Wir hatten durch den vorherigen Aufenthalt in der Tenaya Lodge die Erwartungshaltung an eine rustikales, sauberes Berghotel. Was Wuksachi bietet, sind jedoch für europäische Verhältnisse maximal 2 Sterne, alles jedoch für einen (europäisch gedachten Preis für 4-5 Sterne) Der Empfang war kalt, gestresst und unfreundlich. Die Häuser sind relativ weit weg von der Lodge selbst. Die Flure der Wohnhäuser erwecken nicht den Eindruck als würden diese in regelmäßigen Abständen geputzt. Dasselbe gilt für die Zimmer und vor allem auch für die Fenster. Die Bäder sind unschön und ungepflegt mit Duschwannen aus Kunststoff. Das Frühstück war in Ordnung, wird aber in einem (sehr) kalten Speisesaal serviert. Ich würde beim nächsten Besuch ein Hotel im Tal buchen und dafür auch die lange Anfahrt in Kauf nehmen.</review><user_name>Felix Hirt<//user_name>< Rate>

We experienced the rudest check-in in almost 40 years of travelling around the world. The lady at the front desk told us in an arrogant and smug tone that the phones are not working, the internet will be slow due to a satellite link and that we have to remove all food from the car. Later when we inquired about breakfast options the same lady showed us her total unwillingness to give us the infos - as we interrupted her chat with coworkers. One of the guests helped out. As we didnt want to see these folks again we went to Lodgepole for food and other needs.The lodge is in a great location in the middle of the national park not far from the huge trees. <userid>108465286148279644958<//userid>< Text>
(Translated by Google) Beautiful place to stay and make several walks in the park influencing Moro Rock, Sunset Rock, Topokah Valley and of course visit the bulkier sequoia called General Sherman. The room I was in had two queen beds very comfortable. The hot bath water was very good and in addition the room service was excellent. I should mention that when you stay in Wuksachi you only have the option of having breakfast, lunch and dinner in the restaurant of the place. It is a little expensive, but waiting to get good food in such a repoto place. The dining options specifically were very good. Breakfast not so good. And lunch I can not comment since I did not treat it. Finally it is important to remember chains for the tires of the car during the winter since the snowfalls are common during the cold season.

(Original)
Lugar hermoso para hospedarse y lograr hacer varias caminatas en el parque influyendo Moro Rock, Sunset Rock, Topokah Valley y por supuesto visitar al secoya mas voluminoso llamado General Sherman. La habitación en la cual estuve tenía dos camas tamaño queen muy comodas. El agua del baño caliente estuve muy buena y adicionalmente el servicio del cuarto fue excelente. Debo mencionar que al hospedarse en Wuksachi uno solo tiene la opción de desayunar, almorzar y cenar en el restaurante del lugar. Es un poco caro, pero esperando para obtener buena comida en un lugar tan repoto. Las opciones de cenar específicamente fueron muy buenas. El desayuno no tan bueno. Y de almuerzo no puedo comentar ya que no lo traté. Finalmente es importante recordar cadenas para las llantas del auto durante el invierno ya que las nevadas son comunes durante la temporada fria.<//Text>
